  "title": "Giving credit to peer reviewers",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7192b9c7087056f9",
      "text": "How can referees receive credit or recognition for their work, and what form should this take;"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "433331be410c736c",
      "text": "Several potential solutions exist to make sure that the review process does not cause a bottleneck in the current system:\n\n- Increase the total pool of potential referees,\n- Editorial staff more thoroughly vet submissions prior to sending for review,\n- Increase acceptance rates to avoid review duplication,\n- Impose a production cap on authors,\n- Decrease the number of referees per paper, and/or\n- Decrease the time spent on peer review."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "01baa74533a8b800",
      "text": "Other research shows a similar picture, with approximately 70% of respondents to a small survey done by Nicholson & Alperin (2016) indicating that they would list peer review as a professional service on their curriculum vitae. 27% of respondents mentioned formal recognition in assessment as a factor that would motivate them to participate in public peer review. These numbers indicate that the lack of credit referees receive for peer review is likely a strong contributing factor to the perceived stagnation of traditional models - [https://f1000research.com/articles/6-1151/v3#ref-165 f1000research.com]"
    },
